        "old_string": "  \"text\": \"The JavaScript parsing and bytecode compilation chain in SpiderMonkey follows this architecture:\\n\\n## Entry Point: BytecodeCompiler\\nThe compilation process begins in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeCompiler.h` with the `CompileGlobalScript()` function (line 532 in BytecodeCompiler.cpp), which serves as the high-level driver for the entire compilation pipeline. This function orchestrates the parsing and bytecode generation steps according to the architectural documentation in the header file (lines 28-103 of BytecodeCompiler.h).\\n\\n## Parser: Generating AST\\nThe Parser class is defined in `js/src/frontend/Parser.h` (line 1679) and is heavily templatized along the ParseHandler axis (FullParseHandler for full parsing, SyntaxParseHandler for syntax-only parsing) and along the Unit axis (character type). The parser converts JavaScript source text into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) composed of ParseNode objects.\\n\\n## AST Node Types: ParseNode Hierarchy\\nThe AST nodes are defined in `js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h` and include:\\n\\n- **ParseNode** (line 712): Base class for all AST nodes, which is type-identified by ParseNodeKind enum\\n- **UnaryNode** (line 952): Represents unary operations with a single child node (e.g., `!x`, `-y`)\\n- **BinaryNode** (line 1017): Represents binary operations with left and right child nodes (e.g., `x + y`, `x && y`)\\n- **TernaryNode** (line 1115): Represents ternary conditional operations with three child nodes (e.g., `x ? y : z`)\\n- **ListNode** (line 1184): Represents lists of nodes for statements and expressions\\n- **NameNode**, **NumericLiteral**, **StringExpr**, **FunctionNode**, **AssignmentNode**, **ForNode**, and many others\\n\\nEach node type implements a `test()` static method for type checking and maintains position information (`pn_pos`) for source mapping.\\n\\n## Bytecode Emitter: Generating Bytecode\\nThe BytecodeEmitter is defined in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeEmitter.h` (line 210) and emits bytecode from the AST. Key aspects:\\n\\n- Receives the AST from the Parser\\n- Separates bytecode into prologue and main sections (lines 96-98 of BytecodeEmitter.h)\\n- Uses helper classes like ClassEmitter, PropertyEmitter, CallOrNewEmitter for specific constructs\\n- Emits bytecode instructions using various emit methods\\n- The `emitScript()` function (BytecodeEmitter.cpp, line 2354) is the entry point for emitting script bytecode\\n\\n## Bytecode Output: JSScript\\nThe final bytecode is stored in a JSScript object, defined in `js/src/vm/JSScript.h` (line 1787). Key methods:\\n\\n- `JSScript::Create()` (line 1800): Creates a JSScript instance\\n- `JSScript::fullyInitFromStencil()` (line 1818): Initializes JSScript from the compilation stencil\\n- `JSScript::fromStencil()` (line 1826): Allocates and initializes a JSScript with bytecode\\n- `code()` (line 1844): Returns pointer to the bytecode array (`jsbytecode*`)\\n- `immutableScriptData()` (line 1839): Returns the immutable script data containing the bytecode\\n\\nThe bytecode can be navigated using BytecodeLocation (`js/src/vm/BytecodeLocation.h`) which provides utilities for working with bytecode positions within a JSScript.\\n\\n## Data Flow Summary\\nJavaScript source \u2192 BytecodeCompiler \u2192 Parser \u2192 ParseNode AST \u2192 BytecodeEmitter \u2192 Bytecode instructions \u2192 JSScript with embedded bytecode\"",
        "new_string": "  \"text\": \"The JavaScript parsing and bytecode compilation chain in SpiderMonkey follows this architecture:\\n\\n## Entry Point: CompileGlobalScript\\nThe compilation process begins in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeCompiler.h` with the `CompileGlobalScript()` function (line 532 in BytecodeCompiler.cpp), which serves as the high-level driver for the entire compilation pipeline. This function calls `CompileGlobalScriptImpl()` which in turn invokes `CompileGlobalScriptToStencilAndMaybeInstantiate()` (line 302 in BytecodeCompiler.cpp).\\n\\n## Compilation Orchestration: ScriptCompiler\\nThe `CompileGlobalScriptToStencilAndMaybeInstantiate()` function (line 302) instantiates a `ScriptCompiler<Unit>` class (line 172) and calls its `compile()` method (line 955). The ScriptCompiler extends `SourceAwareCompiler` and orchestrates the entire compilation pipeline.\\n\\n## Parser Entry Points: globalBody and evalBody\\nIn `ScriptCompiler::compile()` (line 955 of BytecodeCompiler.cpp), the parser is invoked:\\n- For global scripts: `parser->globalBody(sc->asGlobalContext())` (line 977)\\n- For eval scripts: `parser->evalBody(sc->asEvalContext())` (line 975)\\n\\nThese methods are defined in `js/src/frontend/Parser.h` in the Parser class (line 1679), which is templatized along the ParseHandler axis (FullParseHandler for full parsing, SyntaxParseHandler for syntax-only parsing) and the Unit axis (character type). The parser converts JavaScript source text into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) composed of ParseNode objects.\\n\\n## AST Node Types: ParseNode Hierarchy\\nThe AST nodes are defined in `js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h` and include:\\n\\n- **ParseNode** (line 712): Base class for all AST nodes, identified by ParseNodeKind enum. Contains position information (pn_pos), type information (pn_type), and intrinsic links (pn_next).\\n- **UnaryNode** (line 952): Represents unary operations with a single child node (e.g., `!x`, `-y`, `typeof x`)\\n- **BinaryNode** (line 1017): Represents binary operations with left and right child nodes (e.g., `x + y`, `x && y`, `x = y`)\\n- **TernaryNode** (line 1115): Represents ternary conditional operations with three child nodes (e.g., `x ? y : z`)\\n- **ListNode** (line 1184): Represents lists of nodes for statements and expressions (e.g., statement lists, function arguments)\\n- Specialized nodes: **NameNode**, **NumericLiteral**, **StringExpr**, **FunctionNode**, **AssignmentNode**, **ForNode**, **ClassNames**, **ClassMethod**, etc.\\n\\nEach node type implements a `test()` static method for type checking via pattern matching.\\n\\n## Bytecode Emitter: Generating Bytecode\\nAfter successful parsing, `ScriptCompiler::compile()` creates a `BytecodeEmitter` (line 1004) and calls `emitter->emitScript(pn)` (line 1009) to emit bytecode from the AST.\\n\\nThe BytecodeEmitter is defined in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeEmitter.h` (line 210) and includes:\\n\\n- Constructor that receives the Parser, SharedContext, and CompilationState (lines 341-350)\\n- The `emitScript()` function (BytecodeEmitter.cpp, line 2354) is the entry point for emitting script bytecode\\n- Helper classes like ClassEmitter, PropertyEmitter, CallOrNewEmitter for specific constructs\\n- Separate prologue and main bytecode sections (lines 96-98 of BytecodeEmitter.h)\\n- Methods to emit individual bytecode instructions corresponding to AST nodes\\n\\n## Bytecode Output: JSScript\\nThe final bytecode is stored in a JSScript object, defined in `js/src/vm/JSScript.h` (line 1787). Key methods:\\n\\n- `JSScript::Create()` (line 1800): Creates a JSScript instance\\n- `JSScript::fullyInitFromStencil()` (line 1818): Initializes JSScript from the compilation stencil\\n- `JSScript::fromStencil()` (line 1826): Allocates and initializes a JSScript with bytecode\\n- `code()` (line 1844): Returns pointer to the bytecode array (`jsbytecode*`), which is an array of uint8_t values representing bytecode instructions\\n- `immutableScriptData()` (line 1839): Returns the immutable script data containing the bytecode\\n\\nThe bytecode can be navigated using `BytecodeLocation` (`js/src/vm/BytecodeLocation.h`) which provides utilities for working with bytecode positions within a JSScript.\\n\\n## Complete Data Flow\\nJavaScript source text \u2192 CompileGlobalScript() \u2192 CompileGlobalScriptToStencilAndMaybeInstantiate() \u2192 ScriptCompiler<Unit>::compile() \u2192 Parser::globalBody() \u2192 ParseNode AST \u2192 BytecodeEmitter::emitScript() \u2192 Bytecode instructions \u2192 JSScript with immutable bytecode array\\n\\nThis modular pipeline allows for lazy compilation of inner functions, separate parsing and bytecode generation phases, and optimization opportunities at each stage.\"",
